:synopsis.
:p.This Primer briefly describes how to use BookManager:
:ul compact.
:li.How to invoke BookManager.
:li.How to find books.
:li.How to display books.
:li.How to search books.
:eul.
:esynopsis.
.***********************************************************************
:notices.
:p.This document describes the Rockwell Information Systems Center
implementation of BookManager READ/MVS. The command to invoke
BookManager, and the initial panels which display categories and lists
of bookshelves, were written by Rockwell. The concept of a category is
also a Rockwell invention. Panels with an action bar at the top are all
supplied by IBM.
:enotices.
.***********************************************************************
:preface.
:p.This is one of two complementary documents:
:ul.
:li.:hp2.BookManager Primer: Using Commands:ehp2. focuses on
the use of commands to request BookManager actions.
:li.:hp2.BookManager Primer: Using the Action Bar:ehp2. focuses on
the use of the action bar and pull down menus to request BookManager
actions.
:eul.
:p.Commands are generally better for frequent BookManager users.  The
advantages are:
:ul.
:li.They are faster.
:li.They are more familiar to most ISPF users.
:li.Some BookManager facilities are available only in this form.
:eul.
:p.The action bar and pull down menus are generally better for new or
infrequent BookManager users.  The advantages are:
:ul.
:li.There is no need to remember command names and parameters.
:li.Some BookManager facilities are available only in this form.
:eul.
:p.You may, of course, use a combination of these two methods.
:toc.
.***********************************************************************
:figlist.
.***********************************************************************
:body.
.***********************************************************************
:h1.BookManager Primer: Using Commands
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject=Introduction.Introduction
:p.BookManager provides online access to over 2000 IBM publications.
It also provides access to a variety of ISC and Rockwell Corporate
publications, such as the Corporate Computing Manual (CCM), Technical
Bulletins (TBs), User News, Corporate Policies, etc.
:p.This BookManager Primer provides procedures for accessing the
information in these publications.  The intent is to guide you
immediately into productive use of BookManager. The most frequently used
commands are covered. However many BookManager features are omitted.
See the bibliography for additional information.
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject=Concepts.Concepts
:h3.Hierarchy of Panels
:p.BookManager maintains its books in a hierarchical form:
:ol compact.
:li.A list of categories of bookshelves.
:li.Categories (a category is a list of bookshelves).
:li.Bookshelves (a bookshelf is a list of related books).
:li.Books.
:eol.
:p.The first two of the above are provided by a Rockwell written front
end to BookManager.
:h3.Common User Access (CUA)
:p.BookManager may be the first mainframe based :hp7.CUA:ehp7.
application you have encountered. CUA is a framework which gives all
applications a similar look and feel, regardless of the hardware and
software platforms:
:ul compact.
:li.System/370 and System/390 mainframes
:ul compact.
:li.MVS
:li.VM
:eul.
:li.AS/400 minicomputers
:li.Personal computers
:eul.
:p.IBM's direction is for all software to use the CUA interface.  So
experience with BookManager will be very useful in the future.
:p.The original ISPF interface is command driven. It is oriented toward
selecting actions (e.g., Browse or Edit), then selecting an object
(e.g., a data set or PDS member) on which to perform that action.
:p.CUA is primarily a graphical interface, so only a subset of it is
applicable to non-programmable terminals.  It is oriented toward
selecting an object first, then selecting an action. An example of this
is PDF Option 3.4 (DSLIST): you display a list of objects (data sets),
then choose an action (Browse, Edit, Delete, etc.) to perform on one of
those objects.
:p.This Primer is intended for current ISPF users. It ignores many of
the CUA features. However an understanding of some of them is required.
The CUA elements which are significant in this document are
:hp7.Pop-up Windows:ehp7. and :hp7.Program Function Keys:ehp7..
:h4.Pop-up Windows
:p.Pop-up windows temporarily overlay a portion of the screen. They are
typically used when you must make a decision concerning some action.
:h4.Program Function Keys (PFKs)
:p.In the original ISPF, PFKs perform the same function throughout an
application. This can be wasteful, since often some of the keys have no
meaning in portions of an application. For example RCHANGE (F6/F18)
has no meaning under PDF Browse.  Under CUA, PFK definitions are
associated with a panel. This allows PFKs to be assigned to actions
which are useful in the context of that panel.  To help you keep track
of PFK definitions, they are displayed at the bottom of each panel. For
example:
:fig.
:screen view=bot.
  F1=Help      F2=Split     F3=Exit      F4=Unlink    F5=Notes     F6=Review
  F7=Bkwd      F8=Fwd       F9=Swap     F10=Actions  F11=Retrieve F12=Cancel
:escreen.
:figcap.Example Program Function Key (PFK) Display
:efig.
:h4.EXIT and CANCEL Commands
:p.Note the definitions of :rk.F3:erk. and :rk.F12:erk. above.
:rev refid=one.
You may see :rk.F15:erk.instead of :rk.F3:erk., and :rk.F24:erk. instead
of :rk.F12:erk..
:erev refid=one.
:hp2.Exit:ehp2. is like a cross between the END and RETURN commands. It
ends a function or application. :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. removes the current
panel without processing it, and returns to the previous panel in the
hierarchy. :hp2.Exit:ehp2. is more powerful than
:hp2.Cancel:ehp2..  This can be confusing, because the original ISPF
default definition for F12 was RETURN.
:p.Under BookManager, :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. must be used for pop-up
windows.
:rev refid=one.
:hp2.Exit:ehp2. cannot be used.
:erev refid=one.
:p.:hp2.Exit:ehp2. returns:
:ul compact.
:li.from a book to a bookshelf
:li.from a bookshelf to a bookshelf list (category)
:li.from a bookshelf list to the category list
:li.from the category list.
:eul.
:h3.Hypertext Links
:p.ISPF users are accustomed to "vertically" organized applications.
You go "down" by selecting options from a menu. You go "up" by using
commands such as END or RETURN (or equivalent PFKs).
:p.BookManager has this "vertical" organization (using :hp2.Exit:ehp2.
and :hp2.Cancel:ehp2.), but adds a "horizontal" dimension.  Suppose you
are reading a hardcopy book, and you come across a reference to some
other part of the book.  You might stick your finger in the book to save
your place and then turn to the referenced page.  After you've read the
referenced material, you then turn back to where you left off.  A
:hp7.hypertext link:ehp7. is the softcopy equivalent of this.  You
:hp7.link:ehp7. "horizontally" to referenced material. Then you
:hp7.unlink:ehp7. to return to your previous place. But BookManager has
more fingers than you do, so you can link through several levels.
:p.The important thing to keep in mind is that no matter how many
hypertext links you've invoked, you're still only one level deep
vertically.
:rev refid=one.
Therefore :hp2.Exit:ehp2. or :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. will exit from the book.
:erev refid=one.
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject='Invoking BookManager'.Invoking BookManager
:h3.Command line
:p.BookManager can be invoked from any ISPF command line with the
:hp2.BOOKMAN:ehp2. or :hp2.ROCKLIB:ehp2. command:
:fig refid=command.
:xmp.
COMMAND ===> bookman
:exmp.
:efig.
:pc.or
:fig refid=command.
:xmp.
OPTION  ===> bookman
:exmp.
:efig.
:h3.Information Center Menu
:p.BookManager can also be selected from the Information Center Menu as
:hp7.option 11  ROCKLIB:ehp7.:
:fig.
:screen.
