:h3.Scrolling Subtopics
:p.You can continue scrolling to view the subtopics in order,
using the :hp2.Bkwd:ehp2. and :hp2.Fwd:ehp2. keys.
:h3.Hypertext Links to Subtopics
:p.Or you can select a subtopic by placing the cursor on a subtopic line
and pressing the :rk.Enter:erk. key. This will cause you to move
horizontally via another hypertext link. There will be no movement
vertically.
.***********************************************************************
.cp
:h2 subject='Returning to the Table of Contents'.
Returning to the Table of Contents
:h3.Hypertext Unlink
:p.You can return to the Table of Contents by pressing the
:hp2.Unlink:ehp2. key (:rk.F4:erk. or :rk.F16:erk.). The
:hp2.Unlink:ehp2. key backs you up horizontally one hypertext link at a
time.
:p.Since hypertext links do not change your position vertically, you
cannot use :hp2.Exit:ehp2. or :hp2.Cancel:ehp2.. Either of these
commands will move you upward vertically in the panel hierarchy and
cause you to exit from the book back to the bookshelf.
:h3.The CONTENTS Command
:p.Alternatively you can enter the :hp2.CONTENTS:ehp2. (:hp2.CON:ehp2.)
command:
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> con_____________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:rev refid=one.
:p.The Table of Contents will then be redisplayed at the point where you
left it.
:erev refid=one.
The :hp2.CONTENTS:ehp2. command does not change your position either
vertically or horizontally.
:rev refid=one.
:fig.
:screen.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> ________________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR

 CONTENTS  Table of Contents               &copyr Copyright IBM Corp. 1988, 1993
