.cp
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject='Searching for a Word or Phrase in a Book'.
Searching for a Word or Phrase in a Book
:p.The preceding technique is useful if you know exactly what you're
looking for. Often this is not the case.
:rev refid=one.
:h3.Searching for a Topic with the SEARCH Command
:erev refid=one.
The :hp2.SEARCH:ehp2. (:hp2.S:ehp2.) command will find all occurrences
of a word or phrase.
:p.For example, to search for the word :hp7.BLKSIZE:ehp7., enter:
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> s blksize_______________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:p.You will then see a list of topics that match the word
:hp7.BLKSIZE:ehp7.:
:fig.
:screen.
 .-----------------------------------------------------------------------------.
 |                        List All Topics with Matches                         |
 | Command ===> ____________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR   |
 |                                                                             |
 | Fuzzy matches for: blksize                                                  |
 |                                               Search matches 1 to 15 of 25  |
 | 11.12    BLKSIZE Parameter                                                  |
 | 11.12.1  Subparameter Definition                                            |
 | 11.12.3  Overrides                                                          |
 | 11.12.4  Relationship to Other Control Statements                           |
 | 11.12.2  Defaults                                                           |
 | 11.18.2  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.20.5  DCB Subparameters                                                  |
 | 11.12.5  Example of the BLKSIZE Parameter                                   |
 | 11.20.4  Examples of the DCB Parameter                                      |
 | 11.20    DCB Parameter                                                      |
 | 11.20.3  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.39.1  Subparameter Definition                                            |
 | 11.8.2   Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.56.4  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.8.1   Defaults                                                           |
 |  F1=Help     F2=Split    F4=Text     F5=No Text  F6=Review   F7=Bkwd        |
 |  F8=Fwd      F9=Swap    F10=Explain F12=Cancel                              |
 '-----------------------------------------------------------------------------'
:escreen.
:figcap.Example of Searching for a Word
:efig.
:p.This is a list to topics which match the specified word or phrase.
The list is ordered with the best matches first.  The default is a
:hp1.fuzzy:ehp1. search. That is, BookManager not only searches for the
specified word
:rev refid=one.
or phrase
:erev refid=one.
as entered, but for variations on that word
:rev refid=one.
or phrase
:erev refid=one.
and for
synonyms.
.cp
:h4.Pop-up Window and the Cancel Key
:p."List All Topics with Matches" is a :hp7.pop-up window:ehp7.  You
have now moved downward vertically in the panel hierarchy. You can
change your mind and move upward (return to the previous panel) by
pressing the
:hp2.Cancel:ehp2. key.  Note that there is no :hp2.Exit:ehp2. key.
:h4.Selecting a Topic
:p.You can select a topic from the search list by placing the cursor on
the desired topic and pressing the :rk.Enter:erk. key.
:p.This is :hp8.not:ehp8. a hypertext link.
:rev refid=one.
It is the equivalent of simply flipping to a different page in the book.
:h3.Searching for a Topic with the "Set Up Search" Pop-up Window
:p.You may also enter the :hp2.SEARCH:ehp2 command with no operands.
This will display a pop-up window:
:fig.
:screen.
   .------------------------------------------------------------------.
   |                          Set Up Search                           |
   |                                                                  |
   |                                                                  |
   | Search for . . blksize                                           |
   |                                                                  |
   |  or                                                              |
   |                                                                  |
   | Modify a previous search request:                                |
   |                ____________________________________________      |
   |                ____________________________________________      |
   |                ____________________________________________      |
   |                ____________________________________________      |
   |                ____________________________________________      |
   | Phrase separator . . . . ,                                       |
   | Wildcard character . . . *                                       |
   | Current matching option  1   1.  Fuzzy matching                  |
   |                              2.  Exact matching, any case        |
   |                              3.  Exact matching, including case  |
   |                                                                  |
   |                                                                  |
   |                                                                  |
   | F1=Help F4=Wordchk F5=Synonyms F12=Cancel                        |
   '------------------------------------------------------------------'
 :escreen.
 :figcap.Setting up a Search Request with a Pop-up Window
 :efig.
 :p.Simply type in a word or phrase and press :rk.Enter:erk.. The
advantages of this technique are that:
:ul compact.
:li.You can recall previous search requests.
:li.You have an alternative to fuzzy matching.
:eul.
:erev refid=one.
.cp
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject='Displaying the List of Search Matches'.
Displaying the List of Search Matches
:p.Suppose you are currently viewing the first topic in the search list.
How do you view the second topic? It is tempting to use the
:hp2.Exit:ehp2. or :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. key.  However this will move you
upward vertically, and return you to the bookshelf display. The
:hp2.Unlink:ehp2. key won't work either, because you didn't get here via
a hypertext link.
:h3.Listing Search Matches
:p.The command you want is :hp2.LIST SEARCHES:ehp2. (:hp2.L S:ehp2.):
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> l s_____________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:p.This will redisplay the "List All Topics with Matches"
:rev refid=one.
pop-up
:erev refid=one.
window:
:rev refid=one.
:fig.
:screen.
 .-----------------------------------------------------------------------------.
 |                        List All Topics with Matches                         |
 | Command ===> ____________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR   |
 |                                                                             |
 | Fuzzy matches for: blksize                                                  |
 |                                               Search matches 1 to 15 of 25  |
 | 11.12    BLKSIZE Parameter                                                  |
 | 11.12.1  Subparameter Definition                                            |
 | 11.12.3  Overrides                                                          |
 | 11.12.4  Relationship to Other Control Statements                           |
 | 11.12.2  Defaults                                                           |
 | 11.18.2  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.20.5  DCB Subparameters                                                  |
 | 11.12.5  Example of the BLKSIZE Parameter                                   |
 | 11.20.4  Examples of the DCB Parameter                                      |
 | 11.20    DCB Parameter                                                      |
 | 11.20.3  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.39.1  Subparameter Definition                                            |
 | 11.8.2   Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.56.4  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.8.1   Defaults                                                           |
 |  F1=Help     F2=Split    F4=Text     F5=No Text  F6=Review   F7=Bkwd        |
 |  F8=Fwd      F9=Swap    F10=Explain F12=Cancel                              |
 '-----------------------------------------------------------------------------'
:escreen.
:figcap.Example of Result of the List Searches Command
:efig.
:p.The cursor will be placed on the topic following the one you just
displayed. You can then select another topic from the list. Or you can
:hp2.Cancel:ehp2. the pop-up window.
:erev refid=one.
.***********************************************************************
.cp
:h2 subject='Displaying Consecutive Topics from the list of Search Matches'.
Displaying Consecutive Topics from the List of Search Matches
:p.If you want to display consecutive topics in the list, it is
cumbersome to return to the list for each topic.
:h3.The FIND Command
:p.An alternative is the :hp2.FIND:ehp2. (:hp2.F:ehp2.) command. When
used this way, BookManager's :hp2.FIND:ehp2.  command is similar to
ISPF's RFIND command. Note that there is
:hp8.no&rbl.RFIND&rbl.key:ehp8..
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> f_______________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:p.Each time you issue the :hp2.FIND:ehp2. command, the next search
topic will be displayed.
:p.Even this short cut is cumbersome if you want to scan quickly through
many items in the list.
:h3.The REVIEW SEARCHES Command
:p.An even shorter cut is to use the
:hp2.REVIEW SEARCHES:ehp2. (:hp2.REV S:ehp2.) command.
:p.The :hp2.REVIEW:ehp2. command :hp8.cannot:ehp8. be entered on the
"List All Topics with Matches" window. You must first display one of the
topics in the list.
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> rev s___________________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:h3.The Review Key
:p.Once the :hp2.REVIEW SEARCHES:ehp2. command has been entered, you can
use the :hp2.Review:ehp2. key (:rk.F6:erk. or :rk.F18:erk.). The
:hp2.Review:ehp2. key becomes the equivalent of the :hp2.FIND:ehp2.
command (again,
similar to the ISPF RFIND command).
:rev refid=one.
:p.Beware: the initial setting for the :hp2.Review:ehp2. key is
:hp2.REVIEW TOPICSSEEN:ehp2., :hp8.not:ehp8. :hp2.REVIEW SEARCHES:ehp2.
:erev refid=one.
.cp
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject='Searching a Bookshelf'.Searching a Bookshelf
:p.If you are not sure which book(s) contain the topics you want, you
can use the :hp2.SEARCH:ehp2. command on a :hp5.bookshelf:ehp5. display
to search that entire bookshelf. This is quite fast.
:h3.Searching a Bookshelf
:p.For example, to search the entire MVS/ESA 4.3 JES3 Bookshelf for the
word :hp7.blksize:ehp7., enter a :hp2.SEARCH:ehp2. command:
:screen view=top.
   Books  GoTo  Search  Notes  Services  Options  Help
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Command ===> s blksize_______________________________________ SCROLL ===> CSR
:escreen.
:fig.
:p.You will see the following panel:
:screen.
