 | 11.12.3  Overrides                                                          |
 | 11.12.4  Relationship to Other Control Statements                           |
 | 11.12.2  Defaults                                                           |
 | 11.18.2  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.20.5  DCB Subparameters                                                  |
 | 11.12.5  Example of the BLKSIZE Parameter                                   |
 | 11.20.4  Examples of the DCB Parameter                                      |
 | 11.20    DCB Parameter                                                      |
 | 11.20.3  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.39.1  Subparameter Definition                                            |
 | 11.8.2   Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.56.4  Relationship to Other Parameters                                   |
 | 11.8.1   Defaults                                                           |
 |  F1=Help     F2=Split    F4=Text     F5=No Text  F6=Review   F7=Bkwd        |
 |  F8=Fwd      F9=Swap    F10=Explain F12=Cancel                              |
 '-----------------------------------------------------------------------------'
:escreen.
:figcap.Example of Selecting a Book after Searching a Bookshelf
:efig.
:p.You may then proceed in the same way as if you had entered a Search
command for a book.
:h4.Cancel and Exit
:p.Vertical movement is a bit more complicated.
:p.If you attempt to :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. the above panel, the "Set Up
Searches" panel will be displayed. A second :hp2.Cancel:ehp2. will
display the Table of Contents of the book. When you :hp2.Exit:ehp2. (or
:hp2.Cancel:ehp2.)  the book, the "List All Books with Matches" panel
will be redisplayed.
:p.As explained above, it takes two more :hp2.Cancel:ehp2.s to get back
to the bookshelf display.
:erev refid=one.
.cp
.***********************************************************************
:h2 subject='Bypassing the Initial Panels (Fast Path)'.
Bypassing the Initial Panels (Fast Path)
:p.The :hp2.BOOKMAN:ehp2. command supports operands which can bypass
one or both of the initial panels.
:h3.Selecting the Default Category (Bookshelf List)
:p.The default category (bookshelf list) may be selected directly. This
is equivalent to displaying the category list, then selecting the
default category.
:fig refid=command.
:xmp.
COMMAND ===> BOOKMAN DEfault
:exmp.
:efig.
:h3.Finding a Category (Bookshelf List)
:p.A :hp2.FIND:ehp2. command can be specified for a string in the
the category list descriptions.
This is equivalent to displaying the category list, then issuing a
:hp2.FIND:ehp2. command.
:fig refid=command.
:xmp.
COMMAND ===> BOOKMAN Find string
:exmp.
:efig.
:h3.Finding a Bookshelf in the Default Bookshelf List
:p.These two capabilities can be combined to find a string within the
default bookshelf descriptions.
:fig refid=command.
:xmp.
COMMAND ===> BOOKMAN DFind string
:exmp.
:efig.
:h3.FIND and DFIND Behaviour
:p.The :hp2.FIND:ehp2. and :hp2.DFIND:ehp2.  commands will display only
those categories which have the specified character string within their
descriptions.  If only one match is found then that item is opened.
:p.The :hp2.FIND:ehp2. and :hp2.DFIND:ehp2.  commands will cause the
BOOKMAN application to exit after the selections are processed. You will
not be returned to the primary BookManager selection list.
.***********************************************************************
